## 5. What is a tensor in this project?

A tensor is just a structured collection of numbers.

In this project, tensors are currently simple rank-2 arrays, so you can think of them like matrices.

The `Tensor` class handles:

- shape tracking
- contiguous memory storage
- indexing by row and column
- direct access to the underlying values

Why this matters:

- tensors are the base data structure of neural networks
- memory layout affects performance

## 6. What is matrix multiplication and why does it matter?

Matrix multiplication is the most important numerical operation in the project.

Why:

- linear layers depend on it
- it is usually one of the main runtime costs in inference
- improving it often improves the whole engine

This project compares three implementations.

### `naive`

The simplest triple-loop version.

Why it exists:

- easiest to understand
- good correctness baseline
- useful comparison point

### `transpose_rhs`

A more cache-friendly implementation.

What it does:

- pre-transposes the right-hand-side matrix
- changes memory access to be more sequential
- improves cache use

Why it matters:

- the math stays the same
- the performance improves because memory is used more efficiently

### `threaded_transpose_rhs`

A multithreaded version of the cache-friendly backend.

What it does:

- keeps the better memory pattern
- splits work across threads

Why it matters:

- large workloads can finish faster
- tiny workloads may not benefit much because threading adds overhead

That last point is one of the important lessons of the whole project.

## 7. What layers were implemented?

The engine supports:

- `Linear`
- `ReLU`
- `Sigmoid`
- `Tanh`
- `Softmax`

What they do:

- `Linear`: matrix multiply plus bias, the main learned transformation
- `ReLU`: keeps positive values, clamps negative values to zero
- `Sigmoid`: squashes values into the range from 0 to 1
- `Tanh`: squashes values into the range from -1 to 1
- `Softmax`: turns final scores into normalized probabilities

## 8. What is the model system?

The project uses a `FeedForwardModel`.

This model is driven by a simple `model.txt` manifest.

Example:

```text
linear w1.txt b1.txt
relu
linear w2.txt b2.txt
softmax
```

This means the project is no longer tied to one hardcoded model.

It can load different feed-forward networks as long as they use supported layer types.

Why this matters:

- cleaner architecture
- easier extension
- better demo value
- stronger interview story

## 9. How does the full pipeline work?

The full project flow is:

1. Python generates example model data.
2. That data includes:
   - input tensor
   - weights
   - biases
   - model manifest
   - expected output
3. C++ loads the same data.
4. C++ runs the forward pass.
5. The C++ output is compared against Python.
6. Benchmarks measure performance of different implementations.
7. The UI displays the model flow, tensors, validation, and performance.

This pipeline is important because it combines:

- correctness
- engineering clarity
- measurable optimization

